# Why Fathom?

Most documents force a choice: [write for the expert or write for the newcomer]{2:write for the expert and lose the newcomer, or write for the newcomer and bore the expert. Fathom dissolves this tradeoff. A single document adapts to its reader — not through dumbing down or gatekeeping, but through [structured depth that the reader controls]{3:structured depth that the reader controls. The format is intentionally simple: plaintext files, two markup constructs, no build tools required. Any text editor can create a fathom document. Any renderer that implements the spec can display one. The format and renderer are fully decoupled — the `.fathom` file is the source of truth, portable and durable}}.

{+2:Consider the use cases: an incident report that serves press, engineering, and legal from one file. A medical briefing that works for patients, clinicians, and researchers. A technical tutorial that's useful to both beginners and experts. A research paper where the abstract, discussion, and methodology are layers of the same narrative rather than disconnected sections.}

{+3:Fathom's design is opinionated about one thing: **replacement, not annotation.** Expanded text replaces trigger text inline — it doesn't appear in a sidebar, tooltip, or popup. This forces authors to write each layer as natural, flowing prose. The result is that a fathom document reads well at every depth, not just at the "default" depth with annotations bolted on. This is harder to write but dramatically better to read.}

The document you're reading is [itself a fathom file]{2:itself a `.fathom` file — plaintext with lightweight markup, served through the Fathom renderer. You can view the raw source, edit it in any text editor, and [host it anywhere that serves static files]{3:host it anywhere that serves static files. The renderer is a single HTML file with no dependencies — no build step, no framework, no server-side processing. Load a `.fathom` file via URL parameter or drag-and-drop, and the renderer does the rest}}.

